00:46:16.409 --> 00:46:18.700
WILLIAM GREEN: So how to
think through this idea of how

00:46:18.700 --> 00:46:21.340
diversified you should
be to control risk.

00:46:21.340 --> 00:46:23.170
AUDIENCE: Yeah,
versus taking risk.

00:46:23.170 --> 00:46:24.570
This is a trade-off there.

00:46:24.570 --> 00:46:26.460
WILLIAM GREEN:
Yeah, I think you've

00:46:26.460 --> 00:46:28.990
focused on really one of the
most important questions.

00:46:28.990 --> 00:46:31.600
And one of the things
that was fascinating to me

00:46:31.600 --> 00:46:33.274
in terms of
interviewing an array

00:46:33.274 --> 00:46:34.690
of these different
great investors

00:46:34.690 --> 00:46:37.890
was actually to see the
difference in the way

00:46:37.890 --> 00:46:40.560
that they had solved
this question.

00:46:40.560 --> 00:46:43.720
So Mohnish for example
had most of his money

00:46:43.720 --> 00:46:47.020
in about five stocks and
had tremendous confidence,

00:46:47.020 --> 00:46:49.147
tremendous knowledge
of these stocks.

00:46:49.147 --> 00:46:50.355
But then one of them blew up.

00:46:52.980 --> 00:46:56.011
So it's risky.

00:46:56.011 --> 00:46:58.390
I think it's one reason
why Mohnish will outperform

00:46:58.390 --> 00:47:01.670
massively over the years, but
I think it can be like that.

00:47:01.670 --> 00:47:03.210
And so you for
Mohnish, because he

00:47:03.210 --> 00:47:08.210
has this extraordinary
temperament, it's feasible.

00:47:08.210 --> 00:47:11.660
So I said to Mohnish about
the financial crisis, I said,

00:47:11.660 --> 00:47:14.556
how did you deal with the
stress of the financial crisis?

00:47:14.556 --> 00:47:16.430
Because at one point
his fund, his hedge fund

00:47:16.430 --> 00:47:17.940
was massively down.

00:47:17.940 --> 00:47:20.190
And he said oh, I
don't feel stress.

00:47:20.190 --> 00:47:23.270
And I actually don't
think that's true.

00:47:23.270 --> 00:47:24.730
I think it may have
been true then,

00:47:24.730 --> 00:47:25.960
but I think there
are circumstances

00:47:25.960 --> 00:47:28.660
where even for Mohnish or even
for Bill Miller, these guys who

00:47:28.660 --> 00:47:31.120
are very unemotional, you
can get to a situation

00:47:31.120 --> 00:47:33.095
where a sufficient
number of things

00:47:33.095 --> 00:47:35.220
can go wrong that actually
it becomes very painful.

00:47:35.220 --> 00:47:38.890
And so I think even for
people like Mohnish who

00:47:38.890 --> 00:47:41.430
have an extraordinary
temperament,

00:47:41.430 --> 00:47:45.000
you have to be aware of the
dangers of overconfidence.

00:47:47.710 --> 00:47:52.970
And I talked to people like
Joel Greenblatt about this.

00:47:52.970 --> 00:47:56.515
And Joel had 80%-- Joel is
one of the greatest hedge fund

00:47:56.515 --> 00:47:57.460
managers of all time.

00:47:57.460 --> 00:48:00.040
And Joel had 80%
of his money in six

00:48:00.040 --> 00:48:02.310
to eight stocks for
much of his career.

00:48:02.310 --> 00:48:06.750
And he said, every few weeks
the portfolio might go down

00:48:06.750 --> 00:48:08.500
30% in a couple of weeks.

00:48:08.500 --> 00:48:10.414
And he said it was fine for him.

00:48:10.414 --> 00:48:11.330
He could cope with it.

00:48:11.330 --> 00:48:13.831
But he said he actually returned
a lot of the shareholders'

00:48:13.831 --> 00:48:14.330
money.

00:48:14.330 --> 00:48:15.900
After five years he
returned half the money.

00:48:15.900 --> 00:48:17.920
And after 10 years he
returned all of the money.

00:48:17.920 --> 00:48:20.320
So the only shareholders
were him and his family

00:48:20.320 --> 00:48:21.810
and his partners.

00:48:21.810 --> 00:48:24.700
And he said if the family lost
money or friends lost money,

00:48:24.700 --> 00:48:26.560
he would just help them out.

00:48:26.560 --> 00:48:27.940
And so it was OK.

00:48:27.940 --> 00:48:33.080
So I think the point
is, you kind of have

00:48:33.080 --> 00:48:37.614
to look at your own temperament
and say how unemotional am I.

00:48:37.614 --> 00:48:40.030
And one of the things my friend
Guy Spier was saying to me

00:48:40.030 --> 00:48:42.440
recently is you can
actually get to a point

00:48:42.440 --> 00:48:46.010
where you are emotionally
flooded, where you can actually

00:48:46.010 --> 00:48:48.334
reach a point where, if a
sufficient number of things

00:48:48.334 --> 00:48:50.000
can go wrong at the
same time, that it's

00:48:50.000 --> 00:48:53.510
very hard to be rational,
to make rational decisions.

00:48:53.510 --> 00:48:57.090
And his view is that
you want to try always

00:48:57.090 --> 00:48:58.620
to be the last man standing.

00:48:58.620 --> 00:49:01.280
And he said you
look at Buffett, who

00:49:01.280 --> 00:49:05.340
has 10 times more capital
in his insurance business

00:49:05.340 --> 00:49:06.130
than anyone else.

00:49:06.130 --> 00:49:08.450
He's basically set it
up so he's antifragile.

00:49:08.450 --> 00:49:12.014
So he'll survive
whatever goes wrong.

00:49:12.014 --> 00:49:13.930
And so Guy's view is,
you want to kind of look

00:49:13.930 --> 00:49:20.440
at what everyone else is doing,
what the people you really

00:49:20.440 --> 00:49:22.390
admire, where they
are on the risk curve.

00:49:22.390 --> 00:49:24.590
And then he said, just
do less than them.

00:49:24.590 --> 00:49:29.254
And I think it's a really
interesting idea that

00:49:29.254 --> 00:49:31.090
yeah, if you're
super constrained,

00:49:31.090 --> 00:49:33.970
if you're incredibly smart, you
can get unbelievable returns.

00:49:33.970 --> 00:49:36.040
But I think for
most of us if you

00:49:36.040 --> 00:49:40.210
want to survive over not
one cycle but 20, 30, 40,

00:49:40.210 --> 00:49:46.170
50 years as an investor, I
think diversification and just

00:49:46.170 --> 00:49:47.564
saying, what do I know.

00:49:47.564 --> 00:49:48.480
What if it goes wrong?

00:49:48.480 --> 00:49:49.510
What if I'm wrong?

00:49:49.510 --> 00:49:51.870
There's a French
investor I interviewed,

00:49:51.870 --> 00:49:56.740
a guy called Francois
[INAUDIBLE], who said to me,

00:49:56.740 --> 00:50:00.650
I have three principles--
doubt, doubt, and doubt.

00:50:00.650 --> 00:50:03.420
And I think it's kind of
helpful to doubt yourself.

00:50:03.420 --> 00:50:05.610
And I think
diversification-- it's just

00:50:05.610 --> 00:50:10.740
kind of rational to say
yeah, but if this company

00:50:10.740 --> 00:50:15.230
I own, if I'm wrong, what
are the consequences?

00:50:15.230 --> 00:50:17.940
And one of the things Irving
Kahn said to me that I thought

00:50:17.940 --> 00:50:21.790
was really interesting, he said,
the single most important piece

00:50:21.790 --> 00:50:26.050
of financial advice I can share
is to focus on the downside.

00:50:26.050 --> 00:50:31.010
And he said, you know,
the trouble these days

00:50:31.010 --> 00:50:32.594
is that people can
gallop really fast.

00:50:32.594 --> 00:50:34.968
But he said they don't really
know what direction they're

00:50:34.968 --> 00:50:35.810
galloping in.

00:50:35.810 --> 00:50:40.680
And he said if you really
focus on the downside,

00:50:40.680 --> 00:50:42.600
and he said you have
reasonable returns

00:50:42.600 --> 00:50:44.420
and you avoid
terrible losses, he

00:50:44.420 --> 00:50:46.840
said you'll outperform all
of your gambler friends.

00:50:46.840 --> 00:50:49.150
And he said it's also a
good cure for your sleeping

00:50:49.150 --> 00:50:49.935
problems.

00:50:49.935 --> 00:50:51.310
AUDIENCE: I think
you interviewed

00:50:51.310 --> 00:50:53.570
Bill Ackman for your book.

00:50:53.570 --> 00:50:55.895
Would you please tell
us something about him,

00:50:55.895 --> 00:50:57.864
and do you think
he will survive?

00:50:57.864 --> 00:50:59.780
WILLIAM GREEN: Yeah, I
do think he'll survive.

00:50:59.780 --> 00:51:03.600
I think Ackman is
remarkably smart.

00:51:03.600 --> 00:51:05.430
I think he's a very
brilliant analyst.

00:51:05.430 --> 00:51:07.480
He's got a very brilliant mind.

00:51:07.480 --> 00:51:11.680
I think as with all of
these great investors,

00:51:11.680 --> 00:51:13.170
they're flawed.

00:51:13.170 --> 00:51:15.560
They're not perfect.

00:51:15.560 --> 00:51:17.635
They make mistakes.

00:51:17.635 --> 00:51:21.210
And his mistake with
Valeant-- so far

00:51:21.210 --> 00:51:24.380
it's turned out to be
a really dire mistake.

00:51:24.380 --> 00:51:27.550
You could say that's
a kind of bull market

00:51:27.550 --> 00:51:29.520
phenomenon of over confidence.

00:51:29.520 --> 00:51:33.600
But he's always been taking
these very contrary positions

00:51:33.600 --> 00:51:34.660
that are very aggressive.

00:51:34.660 --> 00:51:36.880
And it's part of his character.

00:51:36.880 --> 00:51:41.500
And I think Bill has a very
interesting personality.

00:51:41.500 --> 00:51:43.780
He's very combative
in certain ways.

00:51:43.780 --> 00:51:49.680
And he's prepared to go into
these very difficult situations

00:51:49.680 --> 00:51:54.920
where, with something like
Herbalife where he thinks

00:51:54.920 --> 00:51:56.650
this company's a fraud
and a Ponzi scheme

00:51:56.650 --> 00:51:58.630
and I'm going to take it down.

00:51:58.630 --> 00:52:01.330
And he has spent
over $50 million

00:52:01.330 --> 00:52:03.870
on this campaign to
bring down Herbalife.

00:52:03.870 --> 00:52:07.280
And so I think he has a
very distinctive approach.

00:52:07.280 --> 00:52:09.280
And one of the things he
said to me about money,

00:52:09.280 --> 00:52:12.417
he said the reason I wanted
to get rich from very early on

00:52:12.417 --> 00:52:14.000
was so that I would
have independence.

00:52:14.000 --> 00:52:16.290
He said it was so that I
could say what I believe,

00:52:16.290 --> 00:52:19.830
so that I could act in a
way that I believe is right.

00:52:19.830 --> 00:52:23.790
And so he really embodies
this idea of the willingness

00:52:23.790 --> 00:52:26.374
to be lonely, the willingness
to take idiosyncratic positions.

00:52:26.374 --> 00:52:28.498
And that's going to mean
there are times where he's

00:52:28.498 --> 00:52:29.880
going to look really stupid.

00:52:29.880 --> 00:52:32.990
But there were
times where Buffett

00:52:32.990 --> 00:52:34.814
looked stupid in
the late '90s where

00:52:34.814 --> 00:52:36.230
he refused to buy
any tech stocks,

00:52:36.230 --> 00:52:38.563
where Eveillard looked stupid,
where Don Yacktman looked

00:52:38.563 --> 00:52:39.630
stupid.

00:52:39.630 --> 00:52:43.840
Eveillard's assets went down
from I think $6 billion to $2

00:52:43.840 --> 00:52:48.580
billion during the tech
bubble in the late '90s.

00:52:48.580 --> 00:52:49.780
Everyone abandoned him.

00:52:49.780 --> 00:52:52.250
He said to me that one
of the senior executives

00:52:52.250 --> 00:52:54.840
at his company said,
well, Jean-Marie,

00:52:54.840 --> 00:52:56.730
he's half senile anyway.

00:52:56.730 --> 00:52:59.750
And Jean-Marie said
to me, I was 59.

00:52:59.750 --> 00:53:03.040
And so I think one of the things
that's really striking to me

00:53:03.040 --> 00:53:05.850
is that there are always periods
where these great investors

00:53:05.850 --> 00:53:08.110
look like idiots.

00:53:08.110 --> 00:53:13.000
And my money is on
Ackman, just in terms

00:53:13.000 --> 00:53:16.150
of his intellect, his
analytical brilliance,

00:53:16.150 --> 00:53:20.160
and he's got a kind of in
inner toughness to him.

00:53:20.160 --> 00:53:24.614
And I think the real
lesson for-- you know,

00:53:24.614 --> 00:53:26.780
there are multiple lessons
of the Valeant situation.

00:53:26.780 --> 00:53:29.480
But I think the hubris
and the overconfidence one

00:53:29.480 --> 00:53:32.140
is important, the
unknowability of the future.

00:53:32.140 --> 00:53:34.060
Peter Lynch was looking
through some old notes

00:53:34.060 --> 00:53:36.675
from an interview I had
Peter Lynch the other day.

00:53:36.675 --> 00:53:39.415
And well, the interview
was about 18 years ago,

00:53:39.415 --> 00:53:41.290
but I was looking at
the notes the other day.

00:53:41.290 --> 00:53:44.940
And Lynch said to me, he
bet on some company in 1969

00:53:44.940 --> 00:53:48.800
where he said, Ned Johnson
was not yet running Fidelity

00:53:48.800 --> 00:53:52.946
but was then running
a fund there.

00:53:52.946 --> 00:53:55.180
And Lynch pitched
this stock to him

00:53:55.180 --> 00:53:57.940
that was an apparel
company that was great.

00:53:57.940 --> 00:54:01.350
He said it had the cover
of Vogue three times.

00:54:01.350 --> 00:54:04.020
And their earnings, it
was like a record year.

00:54:04.020 --> 00:54:07.200
And he said then the
movie, what was it,

00:54:07.200 --> 00:54:08.810
"Bonnie and Clyde" comes out.

00:54:08.810 --> 00:54:10.520
And he says Faye
Dunaway is wearing

00:54:10.520 --> 00:54:13.550
these incredible long
pleated 1930s skirts.

00:54:13.550 --> 00:54:16.440
And it totally and
utterly changes fashion.

00:54:16.440 --> 00:54:18.680
And he said in the
same year this company

00:54:18.680 --> 00:54:21.090
had record earnings, the
company went bankrupt.

00:54:21.090 --> 00:54:25.299
And he said he talked
to Ned Johnson about it,

00:54:25.299 --> 00:54:26.840
and he said Ned
Johnson just laughed.

00:54:26.840 --> 00:54:28.631
And he said yeah,
sometimes this stuff just

00:54:28.631 --> 00:54:29.970
comes out of left field.

00:54:29.970 --> 00:54:35.450
And so I think this sort of
healthy awareness of the fact

00:54:35.450 --> 00:54:37.400
that the jack of spades
can actually jump out

00:54:37.400 --> 00:54:40.620
of the pack of cards and
squirt cider in your ear,

00:54:40.620 --> 00:54:46.650
it's useful to retain that
sense of our own fallibility.

00:54:46.650 --> 00:54:48.290
AUDIENCE: During
the times when you

00:54:48.290 --> 00:54:51.050
said these investors
would look stupid,

00:54:51.050 --> 00:54:54.930
there seems to be two
kind of categories.

00:54:54.930 --> 00:54:57.090
One is category
where they decided

00:54:57.090 --> 00:55:00.290
they don't want to participate
in irrationality they see,

00:55:00.290 --> 00:55:03.630
like Don Yacktman or Eveillard.

00:55:03.630 --> 00:55:06.690
And then the second
one is where they

00:55:06.690 --> 00:55:08.490
seem to be confident
about something,

00:55:08.490 --> 00:55:10.680
but then it eventually
builds up on them.

00:55:10.680 --> 00:55:16.540
So say Bill Miller, Valeant
example that you gave.

00:55:16.540 --> 00:55:18.920
In those cases
where they're taking

00:55:18.920 --> 00:55:25.830
a bet where they're kind of
alone, how important is it

00:55:25.830 --> 00:55:30.250
where, on one side you want
to be kind of confident,

00:55:30.250 --> 00:55:34.290
but the humanity is confidence
doesn't go into arrogance.

00:55:34.290 --> 00:55:38.290
And in several of these cases
there was enough evidence

00:55:38.290 --> 00:55:39.380
that they could be wrong.

00:55:39.380 --> 00:55:44.900
For example, there's a famous
Steve Eisman and Bill Miller

00:55:44.900 --> 00:55:47.980
kind of face off type of
thing where Steve Eisman was

00:55:47.980 --> 00:55:51.380
this young hedge fund
analyst, running company

00:55:51.380 --> 00:55:52.722
that had done all this work.

00:55:52.722 --> 00:55:53.930
That this is really a bubble.

00:55:53.930 --> 00:55:55.990
In the Valeant case
there was enough evidence

00:55:55.990 --> 00:55:58.220
before that all these--

00:55:58.220 --> 00:56:00.780
WILLIAM GREEN: I think it's a
really profound and important

00:56:00.780 --> 00:56:06.380
question you raise, this thin
line between the willingness

00:56:06.380 --> 00:56:10.470
to be lonely and the arrogance
where you say everybody else is

00:56:10.470 --> 00:56:11.930
wrong, I am right.

00:56:11.930 --> 00:56:13.740
And you end up
blowing yourself up.

00:56:13.740 --> 00:56:16.660
And it's a very, very
interesting question.

00:56:16.660 --> 00:56:21.440
You know, I was always a huge
admirer of Marty Whitman.

00:56:21.440 --> 00:56:25.150
And he was an absolutely
brilliant contrarian value

00:56:25.150 --> 00:56:26.080
investor.

00:56:26.080 --> 00:56:30.296
And Whitman-- once
I said to him,

00:56:30.296 --> 00:56:32.670
if you would to own just one
stock for the next 10 years,

00:56:32.670 --> 00:56:33.378
what would it be?

00:56:33.378 --> 00:56:35.050
And he said MBIA.

00:56:35.050 --> 00:56:39.660
And this is the company
that Bill Ackman shorted.

00:56:39.660 --> 00:56:45.336
And Ackman said to me that he
actually-- I think he said,

00:56:45.336 --> 00:56:47.040
I can't remember if
actually met him,

00:56:47.040 --> 00:56:50.786
but I think he told me that
he contacted Marty and said

00:56:50.786 --> 00:56:52.160
to him, I want to
go through this

00:56:52.160 --> 00:56:53.900
and explain to you
why this is crap,

00:56:53.900 --> 00:56:55.280
why it's going to fall apart.

00:56:55.280 --> 00:56:58.459
And Marty kind of dismissed
him and kind of bad

00:56:58.459 --> 00:56:59.500
mouthed him in the press.

00:56:59.500 --> 00:57:02.860
And Marty's a kind of
combustible guy in the way

00:57:02.860 --> 00:57:05.850
that he's feisty.

00:57:05.850 --> 00:57:08.150
And I talked to Marty
about this afterwards.

00:57:08.150 --> 00:57:09.990
And I said, why did you mess up?

00:57:09.990 --> 00:57:14.430
And he said-- I mean,
he's now in his 90s.

00:57:14.430 --> 00:57:19.500
And he said at a certain point
as I became richer and older,

00:57:19.500 --> 00:57:20.949
I became lazy.

00:57:20.949 --> 00:57:22.740
And he said there were
certain stocks where

00:57:22.740 --> 00:57:24.220
I should have sold.

00:57:24.220 --> 00:57:26.740
He said I knew that I should
have sold my housing stock

00:57:26.740 --> 00:57:29.170
before the financial crisis.

00:57:29.170 --> 00:57:31.860
And I kind of didn't
get around to it.

00:57:31.860 --> 00:57:37.181
And Bill Nygren said to me
that this is a full on game.

00:57:37.181 --> 00:57:38.680
He said there are
lots of people who

00:57:38.680 --> 00:57:40.721
have decided I'm going to
go into semiretirement.

00:57:40.721 --> 00:57:41.670
And it's like no.

00:57:41.670 --> 00:57:44.780
He's like, either the switch
is fully on or it's fully off.

00:57:44.780 --> 00:57:48.290
He said it is so
hard at that level.

00:57:48.290 --> 00:57:52.530
And so I think it's interesting
that all of these guys

00:57:52.530 --> 00:57:53.040
screw up.

00:57:53.040 --> 00:57:55.310
Templeton said to me,
however smart you are,

00:57:55.310 --> 00:57:57.270
you're going to screw
up a third of the time.

00:57:57.270 --> 00:57:59.030
And you know, there
was a wonderful moment

00:57:59.030 --> 00:58:02.277
with Bill Miller where
years ago in 2001

00:58:02.277 --> 00:58:04.110
after the financial
crisis where he's making

00:58:04.110 --> 00:58:05.940
these incredibly gutsy bets.

00:58:05.940 --> 00:58:07.580
I said to him man,
you really have

00:58:07.580 --> 00:58:09.452
to have balls to do what you do.

00:58:09.452 --> 00:58:11.160
And he said yeah, you
have to have balls.

00:58:11.160 --> 00:58:14.050
But you've also got to be right.

00:58:14.050 --> 00:58:16.390
And it stuck with me forever.

00:58:16.390 --> 00:58:18.720
And he said, let me
show you this chart.

00:58:18.720 --> 00:58:21.484
And he shows me this chart
of a fund's performance.

00:58:21.484 --> 00:58:22.400
He says, look at this.

00:58:22.400 --> 00:58:26.474
You see the steady monthly
upward trajectory of this fund.

00:58:26.474 --> 00:58:28.890
And then he said, and then it
just collapses and goes down

00:58:28.890 --> 00:58:30.000
90 something percent.

00:58:30.000 --> 00:58:31.990
He said that's Long-Term
Capital Management.

00:58:31.990 --> 00:58:34.080
And he said the thing
that's really hard to tell

00:58:34.080 --> 00:58:36.760
is am I here in my
career or am I here?

00:58:36.760 --> 00:58:40.130
And so I think this idea of
hubris, of just saying yeah,

00:58:40.130 --> 00:58:42.900
I believe this is true,
but what if I'm wrong?

00:58:42.900 --> 00:58:45.900
And this is why the idea
of the margin of safety

00:58:45.900 --> 00:58:47.050
is so powerful.

00:58:47.050 --> 00:58:52.360
And so I think when you look
at people like Irving Kahn, who

00:58:52.360 --> 00:58:54.860
did tremendously
well for decades,

00:58:54.860 --> 00:58:57.550
it's partly they survived.

00:58:57.550 --> 00:58:59.220
They didn't blow themselves.

00:58:59.220 --> 00:59:01.740
And so Irving would have a
tremendous amount of cash,

00:59:01.740 --> 00:59:02.850
often.

00:59:02.850 --> 00:59:05.480
I think at the end he had
about half his money in cash.

00:59:05.480 --> 00:59:07.910
And so yeah, maybe
you underperform.

00:59:07.910 --> 00:59:09.490
But you survive.

00:59:09.490 --> 00:59:13.990
And so I think that idea
of just being resilient,

00:59:13.990 --> 00:59:15.560
of trying to be the
last man standing

00:59:15.560 --> 00:59:17.976
rather than necessarily the
smartest guy in the room, that

00:59:17.976 --> 00:59:18.800
is very powerful.

